1
00:00:00,120 --> 00:00:04,520
Has the Catholic Church helped or has it

2
00:00:02,800 --> 00:00:06,520
hindered the integration of

3
00:00:04,520 --> 00:00:08,440
Italian immigrants in America? It's an

4
00:00:06,520 --> 00:00:10,759
important question that tells us a lot about

5
00:00:08,440 --> 00:00:12,240
how communities are born and grow.

6
00:00:10,759 --> 00:00:16,000
Well, a new study that analyzed

7
00:00:12,240 --> 00:00:18,320
the period between 1890 and 1920 gives us

8
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:19,800
an answer that is not at all obvious. So

9
00:00:18,320 --> 00:00:22,240
let's go see together what the

10
00:00:19,800 --> 00:00:24,599
data tells us. Now, look closely at these two

11
00:00:22,240 --> 00:00:26,279
maps because they are the key to everything. On the

12
00:00:24,599 --> 00:00:29,320
left we see where the Italians

13
00:00:26,279 --> 00:00:31,279
settled in 1920; on the right, where

14
00:00:29,320 --> 00:00:33,399
they built their churches. The

15
00:00:31,279 --> 00:00:35,000
similarity is impressive, isn't it? But

16
00:00:33,399 --> 00:00:37,320
what has this physical proximity between home and

17
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:39,239
church really meant? Was it

18
00:00:37,320 --> 00:00:41,120
a bridge to the new society or

19
00:00:39,239 --> 00:00:43,480
did it end up building a wall, a

20
00:00:41,120 --> 00:00:45,640
kind of cultural bubble? Well, this

21
00:00:43,480 --> 00:00:48,120
is the question at the center of everything. To

22
00:00:45,640 --> 00:00:49,920
understand it well, let's take a step back.

23
00:00:48,120 --> 00:00:53,359
Imagine the scene. Between the end of the 19th

24
00:00:49,920 --> 00:00:55,399
and the beginning of the 20th, more than 4 million

25
00:00:53,359 --> 00:00:57,760
Italians leave everything and cross

26
00:00:55,399 --> 00:00:59,640
the ocean. They arrive in an America that is

27
00:00:57,760 --> 00:01:01,800
almost entirely Protestant and they

28
00:00:59,640 --> 00:01:04,439
bring with them not only their suitcases, but

29
00:01:01,800 --> 00:01:06,840
something very important: their Catholic

30
00:01:04,439 --> 00:01:09,400
faith. And the Church obviously did not

31
00:01:06,840 --> 00:01:11,680
just stand by. In fact, figures

32
00:01:09,400 --> 00:01:13,479
like Pope Leo X and Bishop

33
00:01:11,680 --> 00:01:15,520
Scalabrini, whose words we read

34
00:01:13,479 --> 00:01:17,640
here, got to work.

35
00:01:15,520 --> 00:01:19,200
The goal was very clear: to found

36
00:01:17,640 --> 00:01:21,960
parishes for these new

37
00:01:19,200 --> 00:01:24,280
arrivals. Of course, to give both spiritual

38
00:01:21,960 --> 00:01:26,000
and material support, but above all

39
00:01:24,280 --> 00:01:27,880
to protect Italian culture and faith

40
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:30,280
in a world that often saw them

41
00:01:27,880 --> 00:01:32,119
as strange. Okay, before

42
00:01:30,280 --> 00:01:35,000
diving into the data, let's focus on a

43
00:01:32,119 --> 00:01:36,960
fundamental concept: assimilation.

44
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:38,920
Careful, it doesn't just mean learning

45
00:01:36,960 --> 00:01:41,479
the language; it's a much more

46
00:01:38,920 --> 00:01:43,560
complex process, it means adopting habits,

47
00:01:41,479 --> 00:01:45,600
ways of doing things, and entering into relationships with

48
00:01:43,560 --> 00:01:47,240
the dominant culture. Keeping this in

49
00:01:45,600 --> 00:01:49,439
mind, we can begin to see what

50
00:01:47,240 --> 00:01:51,119
impact the churches really had.

51
00:01:49,439 --> 00:01:53,280
Let's start from everyday life,

52
00:01:51,119 --> 00:01:55,040
from social relations. Did the parishes

53
00:01:53,280 --> 00:01:57,039
help Italians to bond with

54
00:01:55,040 --> 00:01:58,759
their new American neighbors or, on the

55
00:01:57,039 --> 00:02:01,439
contrary, did they end up keeping them a

56
00:02:01,439 --> 00:02:06,640
bit separate? And here, look, comes

57
00:02:01,439 --> 00:02:06,640
the first data point that really makes you think. The

58
00:02:04,479 --> 00:02:09,520
study discovered that where there was a

59
00:02:06,640 --> 00:02:11,560
strong presence of Italian churches, the

60
00:02:09,520 --> 00:02:14,519
probability that an immigrant would marry

61
00:02:11,560 --> 00:02:18,239
someone born in America plummeted—and

62
00:02:14,519 --> 00:02:20,360
not by a little, we're talking about -61%,

63
00:02:18,239 --> 00:02:22,800
it's a huge number that tells us that the

64
00:02:20,360 --> 00:02:24,720
ties within the community became

65
00:02:22,800 --> 00:02:27,160
much, much stronger than those with

66
00:02:24,720 --> 00:02:29,800
the outside. And this trend didn't

67
00:02:27,160 --> 00:02:32,280
stop at marriages; it also concerned the

68
00:02:29,800 --> 00:02:35,160
place where they lived. There was a drop

69
00:02:32,280 --> 00:02:37,319
of 13% in the probability of living in

70
00:02:35,160 --> 00:02:39,959
mixed neighborhoods with neighbors born in

71
00:02:37,319 --> 00:02:42,400
America. In short, the picture that emerges is

72
00:02:39,959 --> 00:02:45,040
clear. The Church strengthened the

73
00:02:42,400 --> 00:02:47,680
so-called ethnic enclaves; it created

74
00:02:45,040 --> 00:02:49,680
stronger communities internally, yes,

75
00:02:47,680 --> 00:02:52,400
but also more isolated from the rest of

76
00:02:49,680 --> 00:02:54,519
society. Well, so on a social level,

77
00:02:52,400 --> 00:02:56,640
the church seems to have acted somewhat

78
00:02:54,519 --> 00:02:59,000
as a brake, but from an

79
00:02:56,640 --> 00:03:01,040
economic and labor perspective, well, here the

80
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:04,760
story becomes more interesting and

81
00:03:01,040 --> 00:03:07,159
complicated. A picture with lights and shadows.

82
00:03:04,760 --> 00:03:09,159
In practice, a compromise was created.

83
00:03:07,159 --> 00:03:11,280
On one hand, the parishes functioned

84
00:03:09,159 --> 00:03:13,280
as an incredible network; they helped

85
00:03:11,280 --> 00:03:15,200
a lot in finding a job, so

86
00:03:13,280 --> 00:03:17,080
they increased participation in the labor

87
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:19,400
market—definitely a point

88
00:03:17,080 --> 00:03:21,319
in its favor. On the other hand, however,

89
00:03:19,400 --> 00:03:23,720
these jobs were often of lower

90
00:03:21,319 --> 00:03:25,239
quality, lower paid, and almost always in

91
00:03:23,720 --> 00:03:27,599
sectors where only other

92
00:03:25,239 --> 00:03:29,680
Italians worked. So more work for everyone,

93
00:03:27,599 --> 00:03:32,000
but fewer chances for career advancement in the

94
00:03:29,680 --> 00:03:35,080
broader market. We have seen the

95
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:37,439
social and economic effects. But why

96
00:03:35,080 --> 00:03:40,120
did all this happen? What were the

97
00:03:37,439 --> 00:03:42,200
mechanisms, the root causes of

98
00:03:40,120 --> 00:03:45,120
this so ambivalent impact of the

99
00:03:42,200 --> 00:03:47,400
Church? Let's find out. The question

100
00:03:45,120 --> 00:03:49,480
is simple and it's the right one. The

101
00:03:47,400 --> 00:03:50,879
answer lies in a double dynamic.

102
00:03:49,480 --> 00:03:52,840
There was a force pushing

103
00:03:50,879 --> 00:03:55,079
from within the Italian community and

104
00:03:52,840 --> 00:03:57,920
another just as strong pressing

105
00:03:55,079 --> 00:03:59,959
from the outside. Here are the two forces.

106
00:03:57,920 --> 00:04:02,959
First, the parish was not just a

107
00:03:59,959 --> 00:04:05,400
place to pray, no, it was the true beating

108
00:04:02,959 --> 00:04:07,480
heart of the community. There, festivals were held,

109
00:04:05,400 --> 00:04:09,840
mutual aid societies were created,

110
00:04:07,480 --> 00:04:11,480
people helped each other and this

111
00:04:09,840 --> 00:04:14,560
obviously strengthened the ties between

112
00:04:11,480 --> 00:04:17,000
Italians. Second fundamental point,

113
00:04:14,560 --> 00:04:19,440
such a visible, organized Catholic

114
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:20,880
community often triggered the

115
00:04:19,440 --> 00:04:23,199
distrust and hostility of the

116
00:04:20,880 --> 00:04:25,000
Protestant majority. And to understand

117
00:04:23,199 --> 00:04:27,720
how strong this hostility

118
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:30,560
could be, we only need one name: Ku Klux

119
00:04:27,720 --> 00:04:33,320
Klan. Precisely in those years, the second

120
00:04:30,560 --> 00:04:36,000
wave of the KKK was active, which was

121
00:04:33,320 --> 00:04:38,280
fiercely anti-Catholic, and the study

122
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:40,120
found a chilling correlation.

123
00:04:38,280 --> 00:04:42,400
Where a new Italian church was built,

124
00:04:40,120 --> 00:04:45,280
the probability increased that the

125
00:04:42,400 --> 00:04:47,320
Klan would open a local chapter.

126
00:04:45,280 --> 00:04:49,600
This makes us understand the enormous pressure

127
00:04:47,320 --> 00:04:51,400
that these communities faced. So far

128
00:04:49,600 --> 00:04:53,759
we have spoken about them, the first

129
00:04:51,400 --> 00:04:56,280
generation, those who boarded that

130
00:04:53,759 --> 00:04:58,840
ship, but what about their children, the second

131
00:04:56,280 --> 00:05:00,360
generation born and raised in America,

132
00:04:58,840 --> 00:05:02,880
what impact did the church have on

133
00:05:00,360 --> 00:05:04,880
them? Well, get ready because this is where

134
00:05:02,880 --> 00:05:07,560
the story takes a totally

135
00:05:04,880 --> 00:05:09,919
unexpected turn. Exactly. If for the

136
00:05:07,560 --> 00:05:12,160
parents the church, in some ways,

137
00:05:09,919 --> 00:05:14,240
slowed down integration, for their

138
00:05:12,160 --> 00:05:17,280
children it played a completely

139
00:05:14,240 --> 00:05:19,120
different role, almost the opposite. This graph

140
00:05:17,280 --> 00:05:21,160
tells the whole story. For the children of

141
00:05:19,120 --> 00:05:23,160
immigrants, growing up in a neighborhood with

142
00:05:21,160 --> 00:05:25,400
an Italian church meant having

143
00:05:23,160 --> 00:05:26,759
higher literacy rates and a

144
00:05:25,400 --> 00:05:29,120
better knowledge of the English

145
00:05:26,759 --> 00:05:31,360
language. The effect was even stronger

146
00:05:29,120 --> 00:05:33,360
if the parish had its own school.

147
00:05:31,360 --> 00:05:35,440
In practice, the same institution that

148
00:05:33,360 --> 00:05:37,520
isolated the parents was giving the children

149
00:05:35,440 --> 00:05:40,080
the best tools to integrate. It's

150
00:05:37,520 --> 00:05:42,440
incredible, right? And so we come to the

151
00:05:40,080 --> 00:05:45,120
end. How do we put together this data

152
00:05:42,440 --> 00:05:47,680
that seems to contradict itself? Has the church

153
00:05:45,120 --> 00:05:50,199
been a brake that stopped the race

154
00:05:47,680 --> 00:05:52,440
or a rudder that gave direction?

155
00:05:50,199 --> 00:05:55,199
The conclusion in the end is much more

156
00:05:52,440 --> 00:05:57,160
subtle than a simple yes or no. The

157
00:05:55,199 --> 00:05:59,319
church didn't just slow things down or

158
00:05:57,160 --> 00:06:01,800
help; it did something much more

159
00:05:59,319 --> 00:06:04,080
profound. It completely redesigned

160
00:06:01,800 --> 00:06:05,960
the path of assimilation. It

161
00:06:04,080 --> 00:06:07,199
protected the first generation, perhaps

162
00:06:05,960 --> 00:06:09,360
paying the price of a certain

163
00:06:07,199 --> 00:06:11,560
isolation, but at the same time it

164
00:06:09,360 --> 00:06:13,599
invested in the future, giving the second

165
00:06:11,560 --> 00:06:16,080
generation the keys to integrate

166
00:06:13,599 --> 00:06:18,440
successfully. And we close with this

167
00:06:16,080 --> 00:06:20,400
question that remains open. Perhaps the

168
00:06:18,440 --> 00:06:22,479
church was not a brake, but a

169
00:06:20,400 --> 00:06:24,120
rudder. A rudder that guided the

170
00:06:22,479 --> 00:06:26,680
great ship of Italian immigration

171
00:06:24,120 --> 00:06:28,800
on a different course, a course perhaps

172
00:06:26,680 --> 00:06:30,199
slower at the beginning, sure, but one that

173
00:06:28,800 --> 00:06:31,759
allowed them not to lose their own

174
00:06:30,199 --> 00:06:34,039
identity and at the same time to

175
00:06:31,759 --> 00:06:36,440
build very solid foundations for the future

176
00:06:34,039 --> 00:06:38,520
of their children. A complex story

177
00:06:36,440 --> 00:06:41,800
that teaches us that integration is

178
00:06:38,520 --> 00:06:41,800
never a linear path.